<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-436-018  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 436 018.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 17 1989 v23 n29 p65(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Cost-cutting, revisited: while often overlooked, improvingdeveloper productivity is a good option.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McGuff, Francis P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Improving the effectiveness with which information services aredelivered will be one of the biggest challenges faced byinformation systems (IS) managers in the 1990s.andP;  One way toimprove this effectiveness is to contain or reduce the costs ofdeveloping and maintaining systems by improving developerproductivity.andP;  The first step in measuring developer productivityis to determine current production levels and costs.andP;  Productivitycan then be improved by implementing computer-aided softwareengineering (CASE) products or by switching development languages.andO;Once the study is completed, management may consider differentmethods to improve cost figures, such as increasing staff, cuttingdepartmental costs and increasing developer productivity withtools such as CASE.andP;  After the level of productivity improvementrequired is determined, new products may be selected.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISCost ReductionCost of ProgrammingMeasurementComputer-Aided Software EngineeringProductivityEquipment AcquisitionDecision MakingGuidelines.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   A sample information systems organization. (table)IS overhead by job function. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>